tda_expert.interpretation: Treat web_sessions.user_id as a foreign key to customers.customer_id. Use this join to attach customer master data to each web session.
Use web_sessions.user_id = orders.buyer_id to link browsing behavior to downstream purchase activity for the same customer.
Use web_sessions.user_id = email_sends.cust_no to connect web activity with outbound email sends for the same customer identifier.
Use customers.customer_id = orders.buyer_id to attach customer master attributes to each order record.
Use customers.customer_id = email_sends.cust_no to join customer master data with email send activity.
Use products.product_id = orders.prod_code to link each order line to its corresponding product record.
Use orders.buyer_id = email_sends.cust_no to connect purchase behavior with email send history for the same customer identifier.
Use conversions.attributed_ad_id = ad_campaigns.ad_campaign_id to attribute each conversion record to its originating ad campaign.
Use conversions.attributed_cmp_id = campaigns.campaign_id to attribute conversions to higher-level campaign identifiers.
Use conversions.attributed_ad_id = ad_performance.ad_cmp_id to connect conversion outcomes with ad performance metrics for the same ad identifier.
Use ad_campaigns.ad_campaign_id = ad_performance.ad_cmp_id to join campaign configuration with its performance metrics.

ontology_concepts.name: leadsHasEmailSend
ontology_concepts.description: Represents the association between sales leads and email communications sent to them. This many-to-one relationship links each lead to the email sends they have received, enabling tracking of marketing touchpoints throughout the lead nurturing process. Essential for measuring email engagement effectiveness and optimizing lead conversion strategies.

definition.business_rule: A lead may receive multiple email sends; each email send is associated with a specific customer identifier

reasoning.definition_analysis: The definition is well-structured with clear source/target tables, join keys (cust_id to cust_no), cardinality (many-to-one), and a meaningful business rule. The description explains the business purpose of tracking marketing touchpoints for lead nurturing. Minor issue: the naming 'leadsHasEmailSend' could be more precise (e.g., 'leadReceivesEmailSend').
reasoning.evidence_review: The evidence shows value_overlap detection with jaccard similarity of 0.172 (low overlap) but containment_a_in_b of 1.000 (perfect containment - all lead cust_ids exist in email_sends cust_no). The 100% containment is strong evidence for a valid FK relationship, though the low jaccard suggests email_sends has many more unique values. Confidence of 0.606 is moderate. Match rate effectively 100% for containment direction.
reasoning.consistency_check: The naming follows camelCase convention ('leadsHasEmailSend'). The concept type 'link_type' is appropriate. Join keys are clearly specified. No conflicts with other concepts detected. Minor: 'Has' verb could be more descriptive of the relationship nature.
reasoning.completeness_audit: All required fields are present: source, target, join_keys, cardinality, business_rule, source_tables, source_evidence, confidence, and status. The definition includes comprehensive metadata. Algorithmic assessment is complete with all scoring dimensions.

feedback: Strong containment (100%) validates the FK relationship direction from leads to email_sends
Consider renaming to 'leadReceivesEmailSend' for clearer semantic meaning
Low jaccard (0.172) is expected for many-to-one relationships where target table has broader coverage
improvements_needed: Optional: Add inverse relationship definition for bidirectional navigation
quality_judge.justification: The 100% containment rate provides strong evidence that this is a valid foreign key relationship. The definition is complete and well-documented. While the overall confidence (0.606) is moderate, the perfect containment score indicates reliable data linkage. Approved for production use with minor naming suggestion.

action_backlog.title: Enforce FK constraint between conversions.campaign_id and ad_campaigns.id
action_backlog.description:
Implement and roll out a formal foreign key constraint from conversions.campaign_id to ad_campaigns.id to ensure all recorded conversions are tied to a valid ad campaign. Steps:
1) Profile current data to quantify orphaned conversions (conversions.campaign_id not present in ad_campaigns.id) and export a remediation report.
2) Clean up or decide on handling strategy for existing orphaned records (e.g., map to a fallback campaign, mark as invalid, or delete based on business rules).
3) Add the FK constraint in the database schema (including ON DELETE/UPDATE behavior, typically RESTRICT or CASCADE based on marketing requirements).
4) Update ETL/ingestion pipelines to fail fast or route to a quarantine table when invalid campaign_ids are ingested.
5) Validate in staging, then deploy to production with a rollback plan and monitoring for constraint violations.
This will improve referential integrity for marketing attribution, reporting accuracy, and downstream analytics in the e_commerce domain.

action_backlog.title: Document conversion-to-campaign attribution logic and lineage
action_backlog.description:
Create clear, version-controlled documentation of how conversions are attributed to ad campaigns in the e_commerce analytics stack. Scope:
1) Describe the logical model: how conversions.campaign_id is populated (e.g., last-click, first-click, multi-touch rules), and how it relates to ad_campaigns.id.
2) Document data lineage: from raw tracking events (e.g., web/app events, ad platform exports) through ETL/ELT jobs into the conversions and ad_campaigns tables.
3) Specify edge-case handling: missing campaign_id, invalid IDs, default/fallback campaigns, and how these are treated in reports.
4) Include the new FK constraint behavior and any data quality checks (e.g., what happens when a campaign is deleted or ends).
5) Publish documentation in the agreed knowledge base (e.g., Confluence, internal wiki, data catalog) and link it to the conversions and ad_campaigns datasets.
This documentation will enable marketing analysts and stakeholders to correctly interpret conversion metrics and understand limitations of the attribution model.

action_backlog.title: Implement monitoring and alerts for orphaned conversions
action_backlog.description:
Set up automated monitoring to detect and alert on conversions that reference non-existent campaigns, ensuring ongoing data quality after the FK enforcement. Steps:
1) Define a metric for orphaned conversions (e.g., daily count and percentage of conversions where campaign_id has no matching ad_campaigns.id, using a left join or FK violation logs).
2) Implement a scheduled data quality check (SQL or data quality tool) that runs at least daily on the conversions and ad_campaigns tables.
3) Configure alert thresholds (e.g., any non-zero orphaned conversions after initial cleanup, or >0.1% of daily conversions) and notification channels (Slack/email to data and marketing owners).
4) Log historical metrics for trend analysis and incident post-mortems.
5) Integrate with incident management where applicable (e.g., create tickets automatically when thresholds are breached).
This monitoring will quickly surface ingestion or integration issues that could degrade marketing attribution accuracy.

policy_rules.condition: SELECT COUNT(*) / TOTAL_COUNT * 100 FROM customers WHERE customer_name IS NOT NULL AND LENGTH(TRIM(customer_name)) > 0
policy_rules.description: Ensures customer names are present and not empty strings to maintain CRM integrity.

policy_rules.condition: SELECT COUNT(*) / TOTAL_COUNT * 100 FROM customers WHERE email REGEXP '^[A-Za-z0-9._%+-]+@[A-Za-z0-9.-]+\.[A-Za-z]{2,}$'
policy_rules.description: Validates email format to ensure deliverability of marketing campaigns and transactional emails.

policy_rules.condition: SELECT COUNT(*) / TOTAL_COUNT * 100 FROM customers WHERE signup_date <= CURRENT_DATE AND signup_date >= '2000-01-01'
policy_rules.description: Ensures signup dates are not in the future and fall within a realistic business timeframe.

policy_rules.condition: SELECT COUNT(*) / TOTAL_COUNT * 100 FROM products WHERE price > 0
policy_rules.description: Prevents products with zero or negative prices from being listed, protecting revenue.

policy_rules.condition: SELECT COUNT(*) / TOTAL_COUNT * 100 FROM products WHERE margin_rate >= 0.05
policy_rules.description: Flags products with dangerously low margins (<5%) to prevent profitability erosion.

policy_rules.condition: SELECT COUNT(*) / TOTAL_COUNT * 100 FROM orders WHERE buyer_id IN (SELECT id FROM customers)
policy_rules.description: Ensures every order is linked to a valid existing customer record.

policy_rules.condition: SELECT COUNT(*) / TOTAL_COUNT * 100 FROM orders WHERE quantity > 0 AND quantity < 1000
policy_rules.description: Detects unusually high order quantities that may indicate fraud or data entry errors.
Alerts if order volume deviates by more than 50% from the weekly average, indicating potential outages or flash sales.

policy_rules.condition: SELECT COUNT(*) / TOTAL_COUNT * 100 FROM campaigns WHERE campaign_type IN ('Email', 'Social', 'Search', 'Display', 'Affiliate')
policy_rules.description: Enforces standard values for campaign types to ensure accurate marketing attribution reporting.

policy_rules.rule_name: PII Access Control for Customer Data
policy_rules.condition: GRANT SELECT ON customers(email, phone, address) TO ROLE 'pii_authorized_users'
policy_rules.description: Restricts access to sensitive customer PII only to authorized roles (GDPR/CCPA compliance).
